equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives confident valine prediction from buried structural contacts
equation_narrative.story: Position 70 sits in a densely packed hydrophobic environment with 6 structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation of this buried core context, reading predominantly hydrophobic chemistry from neighboring leucines and isoleucines. The logit lens shows fluctuation between small hydrophobic residues (A, L, V) and occasional polar signals (S, T), reflecting the model's encoding of size constraints and local chemistry rather than predictions. At layer 24, the transition to decision-making begins: valine-specific prediction channels activate in the MLP layers 27-32, and V rises from 27% to 99% as neurons encoding branched-chain hydrophobic identity fire strongly. The model's confidence reflects the unambiguous structural context—a buried position demanding a small, hydrophobic residue.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and chemical context from the local environment. Six structural contacts provide strong hydrophobic signal, with attention heads at L32 reading from nearby positions (structural_attn=0.242). Early features encode general hydrophobic character: F1:9146, F1:5480, and F1:1508 (all >44 proj) activate in layer 1. By mid-layers, the representation fluctuates between small hydrophobic residues in the logit lens—alanine peaks at 21% (L12), leucine dominates intermittently, and valine appears at 13-24%—reflecting the model's encoding of size and burial constraints rather than predictions. Co-evolutionary signal is modest (3 positions), suggesting local structure dominates over distant functional coupling. The representation character is consistently hydrophobic-leaning, with occasional polar excursions (S, T) likely encoding the nearby STLHL sequence context.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment with strong local sequence bias toward small branched-chain residues. Structural contacts enforce size constraints while maintaining hydrophobic character.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within contact distance, read by L32 head 4 (2.53 proj, structural_attn=0.242)
Local sequence: STLHL[V]LRLRG motif provides strong hydrophobic context with leucine-rich flanking
Early hydrophobic encoding: F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 (attention, 44-45 proj) establish base representation
Mid-layer features: F18:9820 (20.6 proj) and F18:1558 (18.2 proj) refine structural context

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between layers 24-33 as valine-specific MLP neurons activate. Layer 27 marks the breakthrough: N27:2332 (0.86 proj for V, also votes strongly for A and I) and N27:3050 (0.63 proj for V) fire, pushing V from 27% to 33%. Layers 28-32 see sustained MLP-driven growth with major contributions from N29:297 (1.14 proj), N31:1993 (1.20 proj), and N32:4433 (1.95 proj—the strongest single neuron). By layer 33, V reaches 99.44% as F33:2789, F33:4893, and F33:7625 (all MLP features, 122-131 proj) encode the final high-confidence prediction. Competing hydrophobic residues (I, A, M) are systematically suppressed in the final layers.
decision_phase.transition: At layer 24, the representation shifts from encoding context to selecting an answer. Valine probability jumps from 17% (L23) to 27% (L24), and AA-specific prediction features begin appearing in the MLP stream. Layer 25 shows the first strong V-specific neurons (N25:1842 with 0.41 proj), marking the boundary where perception becomes decision.

candidates.narrative: Valine emerges as the clear winner starting at layer 27 and dominates through layer 33. The decision is driven by MLP neurons encoding branched-chain hydrophobic identity: N27:2332 (0.86 proj), N29:297 (1.14 proj), N31:1993 (1.20 proj), and N32:4433 (1.95 proj—the single strongest contributor). These neurons vote specifically for small, branched hydrophobic residues (V, I, A) but favor V most strongly. Final-layer features F33:2789, F33:4893, and F33:7625 (122-131 proj) lock in the prediction at 99.44%.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L27 (33%), dominant by L30 (45%), final confidence 99.44% at L33
key_evidence: N32:4433 (1.95 proj) — strongest single neuron, votes V > I > W
N31:1993 (1.20 proj) — votes V ≈ E, distinguishes from other hydrophobics
F33:2789 (MLP, 130.8 proj) — final-layer V-specific prediction channel
N27:2332 (0.86 proj) — early decision neuron, votes A ≈ I ≈ V

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine is the closest competitor but never seriously challenges valine in the decision phase. It peaks early at 9.78% (L9) when the representation encodes general hydrophobic character, then rises again to 9.76% at L29 as branched-chain-specific neurons activate. However, I-voting neurons like N30:3250 (0.98 proj for I, 0.66 for V) are outnumbered by V-specific neurons. By L33, I collapses to 0.16% as the model commits fully to valine.
candidates.key_layers: Early peak at L9 (9.78%), secondary rise at L29 (9.76%), final 0.16%
key_evidence: N30:3250 (0.98 proj for I, 0.66 for V) — strongest I advocate, but insufficient
Peaks during general hydrophobic encoding phase (L8-9)
Suppressed by V-specific neurons in L31-33

candidates.narrative: Alanine dominates the logit lens from layers 0-12, peaking at 20.74% (L12), but this reflects the representation's encoding of small hydrophobic character rather than a prediction. The early A signal comes from the model reading size constraints and burial context—alanine is the smallest hydrophobic residue. As the representation refines to encode branched-chain specificity, A declines steadily: 20.7% (L12) → 9.3% (L17) → 4.9% (L23) → 0.16% (L33). The decision phase actively suppresses A in favor of V.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-L11, peaks at L12 (20.74%), declines through L23, final 0.16%
key_evidence: Early dominance reflects size-constraint encoding, not prediction
N12:3101 (0.29 proj for V) begins distinguishing V from A at mid-layers
Systematically suppressed by branched-chain-specific neurons in L27+

candidates.narrative: Methionine rises steadily through the perception phase (0.52% at L0 → 6.66% at L23) as the model encodes hydrophobic burial context, peaking at 16.7% (L25) just as the decision phase begins. This suggests M-voting neurons briefly activate when branched-chain features emerge. However, M lacks the structural support V receives: neurons like N17:3844 vote V > M (0.45 vs 0.30 proj), and M collapses to 0.09% by L33 as V-specific channels dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Steady rise through L23, peaks at L25 (16.7%), collapses by L33 (0.09%)
key_evidence: Peak at L25 (16.7%) coincides with decision-phase onset
N17:3844 (0.45 proj for V, 0.30 for M) — votes hydrophobic but prefers V

candidates.narrative: Threonine shows persistent logit-lens presence through layers 0-23 (11.6% → 15.0% peak at L21 → 6.7% at L23), reflecting the model's encoding of the local STLHL sequence context—threonine appears two positions upstream. This is a clear case of the logit lens projecting sequence identity rather than prediction. Once the decision phase begins, T is rapidly suppressed: neurons like N22:3288 vote against V in favor of T (-0.54 proj), but are overwhelmed by V-specific neurons. T drops to 0.05% by L33.
candidates.key_layers: Persistent through L0-L21 (peaks 15.0% at L21), suppressed L24+ (0.05% final)
key_evidence: Reflects local sequence context (T at position 68) rather than structural fit
N22:3288 (-0.54 answer_proj) votes T > P > L, opposing V

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from encoding general small-hydrophobic character (A-dominated) to encoding branched-chain specificity (V emerges). Alanine drops from 20.7% to 9.3% while valine rises from ~13% to 24.4%. Attention-driven velocity events at L13 (+3.7 attn_delta) and L20 (+1.55 attn_delta) suggest the model is reading structural contacts that distinguish branched from linear sidechains. This is still perception—the model is refining its representation of what chemistry belongs here, not yet deciding on an answer.

The transition from perception to decision occurs here. Layer 24 shows the first negative total MLP contribution (total_answer_proj=-2.09), suggesting competition between candidates. Layer 25 activates V-specific neurons like N25:1842 (0.41 proj), and layer 27 delivers the breakthrough with N27:2332 (0.86 proj) and N27:3050 (0.63 proj) firing strongly. Valine jumps from 27.3% (L24) to 36.5% (L27), marking the point where the model commits to its answer. The MLP stream drives this transition with +4.1 proj at L27.

Final confidence surge as the strongest V-specific neurons fire. Layer 31 contributes +3.34 MLP proj with N31:1993 (1.20 proj) and N31:2906 (1.03 proj). Layer 32 adds +3.21 MLP proj with N32:4433 (1.95 proj—the single strongest neuron). Layer 33 shows anomalous negative velocity (total_delta=-24.78) but this is a logit-lens artifact; the MLP actually contributes +6.21 proj, and final features F33:2789, F33:4893, F33:7625 (122-131 proj) encode the 99.44% confidence. Competing residues (I, A, M) are fully suppressed.

deep_dives.label: Early hydrophobic encoding (L1, L9)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 1 features F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 (44-45 proj) establish the base hydrophobic representation. Layer 9 features F9:5728 (48.8 proj) and F9:1281 (44.7 proj) refine this as structural contacts are read. These encode context chemistry, not predictions.

deep_dives.label: Structural contact reading (L32 heads)
deep_dives.caption: L32 head 4 (2.53 proj, structural_attn=0.242) reads from the 6 structural contacts, providing decisive hydrophobic context. L32 head 7 (-2.15 proj, coevol_attn=0.105) erases competing signals from co-evolving positions. These heads deliver the final structural evidence.

deep_dives.label: Representation refinement (L18)
deep_dives.caption: F18:9820 (20.6 proj) and F18:1558 (18.2 proj) encode the refined structural context as the representation shifts from A-like to V-like character. This is where size constraints and branched-chain specificity emerge in the representation.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset (L24-L25 MLPs)
deep_dives.caption: L24 shows competition (total_answer_proj=-2.09) with neurons voting for multiple hydrophobics. L25 activates the first strong V-specific neurons: N25:5056 (0.47 proj) and N25:1842 (0.41 proj). This is where perception becomes decision.

deep_dives.label: Valine breakthrough (L27-L28 MLPs)
deep_dives.caption: L27 neurons N27:2332 (0.86 proj) and N27:3050 (0.63 proj) deliver the decisive push, contributing +4.1 MLP proj. L28 adds +4.15 MLP proj with N28:1075 (0.55 proj) and N28:1562 (0.47 proj). Valine rises from 27% to 41% across these two layers.

deep_dives.label: Final confidence (L31-L33 MLPs)
deep_dives.caption: L31 N31:1993 (1.20 proj), N31:2906 (1.03 proj), and N31:3323 (1.02 proj) push V to 85%. L32 N32:4433 (1.95 proj—the strongest single neuron) and N32:5099 (0.86 proj) drive V to 95%. These neurons encode branched-chain hydrophobic identity with high specificity.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L33)
deep_dives.caption: F33:2789 (130.8 proj), F33:4893 (126.2 proj), and F33:7625 (126.2 proj) are all MLP-sourced features encoding the final V prediction at 99.44% confidence. These are the model's output channels for valine.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts valine with 99.44% confidence by assembling a clear picture of position 70's buried hydrophobic core environment. Six structural contacts provide unambiguous hydrophobic signal, read primarily by L32 attention heads. Through layers 1-23, the representation refines from general small-hydrophobic character (A-like) to branched-chain specificity (V-like) as the model encodes size constraints and local chemistry. The decision crystallizes in layers 27-32 as MLP neurons encoding branched-chain hydrophobic identity fire strongly—N32:4433 alone contributes 1.95 proj. The high confidence reflects the unambiguous structural context: this position demands a small, branched, hydrophobic residue, and valine is the optimal fit.
